Problem 12.3 {2}{ 2 / 2 }

A student stated that the first-order auto-regressive error models (12.1) and (12.2) are too simple for business time series data because the error term in period t in such data is also influenced by random effects that occurred more than one period in the past. Comment.

Solution:

The error term in period t is a linear combination of the current and preceding disturbance terms. When the parameter is between 0 and 1 indicates that the further the period is in the past, the smaller is the weight of disturbance term in determining the error term in period t.

# Here is generic code that would read in any "Problem" from any "Chapter":

Chapter <- 12 #change this to the chapter you want

# Give it nice column names for conevience:
# Be sure to change pWhatever.Whatever to p11.11 or whatever you used above.
colnames(p12.9) <- c("Y","X1")

Microcomputer components A staff analyst for a manufacturer of microcomputer components has compiled monthly data for the past 16 months on the value of industry production of processing units that use these components (X, in million dollars) and the value of the firms components used (Y, in thousand dollars). The analyst believes that a simple linear regression relation is appropriate but anticipates positive auto-correlation.

a) Fit a simple linear regression model by ordinary least squares and obtain the residuals Also obtain \(s\{b_{0}\}\) and \(s\{b_{1}\}\).

Solution: 
lm(Y ~ X1, p12.9) %T>%
{print(tidy(.))} %>% 
ggplot(aes(X1, Y)) + 
  geom_point(shape = 1) + 
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = F, size = .5, color = "firebrick2") + 
  labs(title = "Simple OLS Model") + 
  theme_bw()
##          term  estimate std.error statistic      p.value
## 1 (Intercept) -7.738516  7.174639 -1.078593 2.990026e-01
## 2          X1 53.953316  3.519672 15.329077 3.817927e-10

\[ \widehat{Y} = -7.7385 + 53.9533X \\ s\{b_0\} = 7.1746 \\ s\{b_1\} = 3.5197 \]


b) Plot the residuals against time and explain whether you find any evidence of positive autocorrelation.

Solution: 
augment(lm(Y ~ X1, p12.9)) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = seq_along(X1), y = .resid)) + 
  geom_point(shape = 1) + 
  geom_line() + 
  labs(title = "Residuals plotted against time", x = "Month", y = "Residuals") + 
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(2,16,2)) + 
  theme_bw()


c) Conduct a formal test for positive autocorrelation using \(\alpha = 0.5\). State the alternatives, decision rule, and conclusion. Is the residual analysis in part (b) in accord with the test result?

Solution:

\[ H_0: \rho = 0, H_A: \rho > 0, D = .857, d_L = 1.10, d_u = 1.37. \\ \text{If } D > 1.37 \text{ conclude } H_0, \text{ if }D < 1.10 \text{ conclude } H_A, \text{ otherwise test is inconclusive.} \]

car::durbinWatsonTest(lm(Y~X1,p12.9))
##  lag Autocorrelation D-W Statistic p-value
##    1       0.5273293     0.8566024       0
##  Alternative hypothesis: rho != 0

Advertising agency. The managing partner of an adverting agency is interested in the possibility of making accurate predictions of monthly billings. Monthly data on amount of billings (Y in thousands of constant dollars) and on number of hours of staff time (X, in thousand hours) for the 20 most recent months follow. A simple linear regression models is believed to be appropriate, but positively auto-correlated error terms may be present.

a) Fit a simple linear regression model by ordinary least squares and obtain the residuals. Also obtain \(s\{b0\}\) and \(s\{b1\}\).

Solution: 
ggplot(p12.13, aes(X1, Y)) + 
  geom_point(shape = 1) + 
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = F, size = .5, color = "firebrick2") + 
  labs(title = "Simple OLS Model") + 
  theme_bw()


b) Plot the residuals against time and explain whether you find any evidence of positive auto-correlation.

Solution: 
augment(lm(Y ~ X1, p12.13)) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = seq_along(X1), y = .resid)) + 
  geom_point(shape = 1) + 
  geom_line() +
  labs(title = "Residuals plotted against time", x = "Month", y = "Residuals") + 
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(2,20,2)) + 
  theme_bw()


c) Conduct a formal test for positive auto-correlation using \(\alpha =.01\) State the alternatives decision rule, and conclusion. Is the residual analysis in part (b) in accord with the test result?

Solution: 
car::durbinWatsonTest(lm(Y ~ X1, p12.13))
##  lag Autocorrelation D-W Statistic p-value
##    1       0.3072624     0.9737425    0.01
##  Alternative hypothesis: rho != 0
